{"cursor":"13527","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox University |name =Gemological Institute of America |image =\n|established =1931 |type =Private, Co-ed |head =Donna Baker |city =Carlsbad\n|state =California |country =United States |faculty =21 Gemology & 9 Jewelry\nArts Instructors |annual tuition =$17,400 (in residence CA/NY), |homepage = }}\n\nThe 'Gemological Institute of America', or 'GIA', is a nonprofit institute\ndedicated to research and education in the field of gemology and the jewelry\narts. Founded in 1931, GIA's mission is to protect all buyers and\nsellers of gemstones by setting and maintaining the standards used to evaluate\ngemstone quality. The institute does so through research, gem identification and\ndiamond grading services and a variety of educational programs. Through its world-\nrenowned library and subject experts, GIA acts as a resource of gem and jewelry\ninformation for the trade, the public and worldwide media\noutlets. [http://www.diamonds.net/news/NewsItem.aspx?ArticleID=42801]\n\nIn 1953 the GIA developed its International Diamond Grading System and the Four\nCs (cut, clarity, color, and carat weight) as a standard to compare and evaluate\nthe quality of\ndiamonds. http://www.diamonds.net/news/NewsItem.aspx?ArticleID=42801\n\nToday, the institute is headquartered in Carlsbad, California and operates out\nof 14 countries, with 12 campuses, seven laboratories and four research centers\nworldwide.\n","linknr":165,"url":"Gemological_Institute_of_America","recorded":1374522479,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Gemological_Institute_of_America&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Gemological_Institute_of_America&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DR